{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b2a425f3-e5c2-45e4-b03b-975497109549","content":"In modern MSTest (v3.8+), use **constructor injection** for `TestContext` and combine it with `[TestInitialize]` for async setup. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IDisposable\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private MyService _service;\n\n    // Synchronous init via constructor (TestContext injected automatically)\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // sync setup here\n    }\n\n    // Async init via [TestInitialize]\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        _service = await MyService.CreateAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task MyTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_testContext);\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_service);\n    }\n\n    // Cleanup (sync) — or use IAsyncDisposable for async cleanup\n    public void Dispose() { /* ... */ }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor** — runs first; use for sync setup and receiving `TestContext` via injection (no `[TestInitialize]` attribute needed on it).\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — runs after the constructor, before each test; supports `async Task` for async setup.\n- **`[TestCleanup]`** or `IDisposable`/`IAsyncDisposable` — for teardown.\n- The old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property-injection style still works but constructor injection is the modern preferred approach.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bf3f1916-0827-43d8-8c21-ae424bb455ef","outputTokens":391,"requestId":"603C:29F7F6:23E717A:268A4F9:6A0311E3"},"id":"64309cea-1289-49e2-aca5-cf13b4bda936","timestamp":"2026-05-12T11:41:37.735Z","parentId":"d62a8640-dfcb-4061-9d34-60940ba29a77"}
